{{COI|date=August 2010}}
'''The Wisconsin Center for the Advancement of Postsecondary Education (WISCAPE)''' was established in 2001 on the [[University of Wisconsin-Madison]] campus by former UW–Madison Chancellor [[David Ward (university president)|David Ward]].<ref name=Heinen>Heinen, N. “A Rare Look Inward.” Madison Magazine, March 2001.</ref>
==Purpose== Ward envisioned the center as “a policy [[think tank]], not just an academic think tank,” that would promote cross-disciplinary research and scholarship on [[postsecondary education]], enhance professional development for those working at colleges and universities, and engage the public in a dialogue about the role of postsecondary education in a democratic society.<ref name=Heinen />
==Areas of focus== Local and national media have since highlighted the work of the center’s staff, scholars, and affiliates on a variety of postsecondary education issues, including [[Student financial aid in the United States|financial aid]],<ref name=Ziff>Ziff, D. “A Study on Grant Students.” Wisconsin State Journal, July 27, 2008. [http://host.madison.com/news/local/article_a1689412-c429-5708-b950-4e0013e5f245.html]</ref> trends in state funding for postsecondary education,<ref>College Connections: A Weekly Radio Program about Higher Education in Oklahoma. “Understanding Funding Trends,” October 20, 2007. [http://www.okhighered.org/college-connection/archives/CC-10-20-07.wma]</ref><ref>Redden, E. “Explaining State Spending on Higher Ed.” Inside Higher Ed, October 11, 2007. [http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2007/10/11/spending]</ref> returns to state investment in postsecondary education,<ref>Trostel, P. “State Fiscal Priorities Disturbing.” Wisconsin State Journal, November 16, 2006. [http://host.madison.com/news/opinion/article_33ade463-3021-53ad-9c63-eab8d5717667.html]</ref> college student transfer issues,<ref>[http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2009/04/17/transfer Moltz, D. “Why Reverse Transfer?” Inside Higher Ed, April 17, 2009]</ref><ref>Ashburn, E. “Disadvantaged Students Can Earn 4-Year Degrees With Key Supports, Study Finds.” The Chronicle of Higher Education, August 9, 2009. [http://chronicle.com/article/Disadvantaged-Students-Can/47972/]</ref><ref>Carey, K. “Carrots, Sticks and Transfer.” Inside Higher Ed, June 23, 2008. [http://www.insidehighered.com/views/2008/06/23/carey]</ref> community colleges,<ref>Viadero, D. “Community College a Research Puzzle. Education Week, September 2, 2009. [http://www.edweek.org/ew/toc/2009/09/02/index.html]</ref><ref>Wisconsin Public Radio. “Transforming America’s Community Colleges,” University of the Air, August 9, 2009. [http://clipcast.wpr.org:8080/ramgen/wpr/uoa/uoa090809.rm]</ref><ref>Finkelmeyer, T. “UW-Madiso